Title: The Interview Official Final Trailer (2014) - James Franco, Randall Park Comedy HD
Comment:
The Interview was better than Team America. The Interview sent a message about not being intimidated(both the material in the film and the story of it's release), thinking for oneself by putting observable facts over emotional appeal, showing people the truth that those people are either blinded to or silenced from discussing, and showing the importance of talking about actual political news instead of unintelligible gossip(Skylark Tonight in the beginning was the anti-example used to get this across). There were it's fair share of sex, anatomy, and comic violence jokes, but(in spite of the fact that Team America had more), those were all just garnish for the important standpoints.
Team America, although I love the scenes with Kim Jong Il losing it, was just "Kill the savages bang bang bang you're dead", and even though it did poke a little satirical fun at that mentality, it was also the main message of the film. It was basically saying, when presented with a threat, abandon all critical thinking and just bring out the bombs. And although celebrities are not MORE credible to give political opinions, they are not LESS credible, but the secondary message of the film was that they are, which is nonsensical. Great comedy, but weak ideas. Overall, I expect better of Parker and Stone.

Comment:
I was kind of disappointed...and put off by all the vulgarity. The "F" word is used in practically every other line (you'll realize this within the first minute) and there are just too many references to sexual organs and porn. Can't you make a funny movie without all your punchlines being about sex and sexual organs? I did enjoy about ten percent of the non-vulgar humor. Some of it was quite funny, but I'll watch Zoolander over The Interview anytime‚Äî it's a thousand times better.

Did the movie mock the North Koreans? For sure it did mock their funny-hairstyled leader, and I'm okay with that‚ÄîI don't like that evil dictator who's worshiped as a god. But I didn't feel like the movie mocked the people. Are the North Koreans (especially the children) starving? Yes, they are. If they show you fat kids, it's all for show. Are the grocery stores filled with plastic fruits and vegetables? Well, they may have some real goods on display in their department stores to show that they are a "prosperous" country, but that's it, they are for display for the media‚Äîyou can't actually buy and use the stuff. I saw all this in documentaries that used hidden cameras.

Save your money and time and watch a more decent movie.

Comment: Okay, there's nothing wrong with making a movie in relation to North Korea or whatever. But the idea of assassinating Kim Jong-un? I know most people and South Koreans (such as myself) would support that but to actually make a movie about it 'just for a laugh' is a bit far. No one knows the actual ending of the movie yet, but no matter how they do it it'll still receive backlash from the public: If they actually succeed in killing him in the movie, they're asking to start a war with North Korea and cause even more worldwide tension. It's also a sad reality for Koreans because this is just a movie, it's a very rare event that he will be assassinated and he will continue to rule North Korea in his selfish ways. If they don't succeed in the movie, just the idea of assassination will cause tension and the whole effort into making the film would've been pointless. It will probably also portray the idea that the North Koreans yet again have more power in some way if they can outthink the CIA and manage to protect their leader in the film. I'm just sick of North Korea being so commercialised and being teased for being a Korean in general. It's a sad history and sad reality for us.

Having watched the trailer, nothing would entice me to watch this movie. Maybe I just don't appreciate American humour.

But when I heard that Sony pulled it¬†as a result¬†of North Korean hacker attacks, I was flabbergasted. I understand that North Korea can't take a joke (how many movies have there been made about assassinating the US President, for Chrissakes?), but for North Korea's hacking efforts to¬†result in sabotaging the fundamental (and universal, IMO) Right to the Freedom of Speech, that's going a bit too far...

I wholeheartedly agree with the phrase attributed to Voltaire: "I disapprove of what you say, but I will defend to the death your right to say it".

The fact that the giant Sony bowed to North Korea's cyber terrorism says a lot¬†about our present¬†day and age...

I appreciate that this is a movie, and a comedy, but...I mean...shouldn't there be a line? We're talking about an absolutely horrible dictator here, whose family (and himself, as well) is the cause for unimaginable suffering.

Not saying we shouldn't parody (and I'm sure the film will make him look bad in the end), but doesn't a movie like this make light of the real tragedy happening right now in the DPRK?

I don't know, its all in good fun, but the vibe from the trailer kinda makes me a bit uncomfortable.
